Translated by Theresa Tan of The Straits Times Translation Desk.]    HIGHS AND LOWS    * The rise of the socialist bloc in the 1950s and the Cold War divided the world into two camps, East and West.    
<STNO>0050</STNO>
Sino-Russian ties entered a honeymoon period but Stalin wanted to call the shots. 
<STNO>0051</STNO>
* In the 1960s, Stalin's successors were still hankering after control over China. 
<STNO>0052</STNO>
By now, China had come into its own, and a fallout was only a matter of course. 
<STNO>0053</STNO>
* A decade later, Mao came up with his "three worlds" theory, and China began moving away from the socialist bloc to begin forging an alliance against Russia, plunging Sino-Russian ties to their lowest point. 
<STNO>0054</STNO>
* In the 1980s, Beijing embarked on reforms and opened its doors to the world, patching up relations with the international community. 
<STNO>0055</STNO>
* The two sides normalised relations in 1989. 
<STNO>0056</STNO>
* But when the Cold War ended in the early 1990s, China remained on high alert against an emerging capitalist Russia. 
